","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England"},"en":{"about 1350–1403":"about 1350–1403","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1357–Male":"1357–Deceased","–1403":"–1403","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1382–1453":"1382–1453","–1441":"–1441","1320–1403":"1320–1403","1335–1375":"1335–1375","before 1375":"before 1375","from 1392 to 1394":"from 1392 to 1394","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","13 August 1377":"13 August 1377","1403":"1403","January 1380":"January 1380","1335":"1335","1357":"1357","August 1395":"August 1395","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1441":"1441","before 1382":"before 1382","before 1380":"before 1380","about 1350":"about 1350","about 1395":"about 1395","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, England","Cumberland, England":"Cumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Curwen","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish and English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place called Culewen (now Colvend) in Kirkcudbrightshire. The family was early established in Lancashire, where it was often pronounced without the <i>-w-</i>; see   Corrin   and   Currin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Corrin","meanings":["Irish and Manx: shortened form of <i>Mac Torin</i>, from Gaelic <i>mac</i> ‘son (of)’ + Old Norse <i>Thórfinnr</i> (from <i>Thórr</i>, the name of the Scandinavian thunder god, + the ethnic designation <i>Finnr</i>). Compare   Turpin  . This name has occasionally been confused with   Corin  .","English (Lancashire): variant of   Curwen  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":32,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Curwen Knt. was born about 1350, in Cumberland, England, his father, Gilbert Curwen IV, was 32 and his mother, Alice Lowther, was 17. He married Ellen Brun before 1380. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1403, in Workington, Cumberland, England, at the age of 54."},"et":{"about 1350–1403":"umbes 1350–1403","1350–1403":"1350–1403","1357–Male":"1357–Surnud","–1403":"–1403","1350–1395":"1350–1395","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1382–1453":"1382–1453","–1441":"–1441","1320–1403":"1320–1403","1335–1375":"1335–1375","before 1375":"enne 1375","from 1392 to 1394":"1392 kuni 1394","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1360":"1360","13 August 1377":"13. august 1377","1403":"1403","January 1380":"jaanuar 1380","1335":"1335","1357":"1357","August 1395":"august 1395","1453":"1453","1397":"1397","1375":"1375","1320":"1320","1441":"1441","before 1382":"enne 1382","before 1380":"enne 1380","about 1350":"umbes 1350","about 1395":"umbes 1395","Workington, Cumberland, England":"Workington, Cumberland, Engla